        "subtype": "bot_message",
        "text": "*[Bug 19091] as.numeric on macOS aarch64 rounds \"0.9999999999999999\" to 1.0 instead of the nearest IEEE 754 double*\n<https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=19091>\n\nDeepayan Sarkar (<mailto:deepayan.sarkar@r-project.org|deepayan.sarkar@r-project.org>) changed:\n\n           What    |Removed                     |Added\n----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n                 CC|                            |deepayan.sarkar@r-project.o\n                   |                            |rg\n\n--- Comment #2 from Deepayan Sarkar (<mailto:deepayan.sarkar@r-project.org|deepayan.sarkar@r-project.org>) ---\nReproducible on M5 as well (using 4.6.1 official binary).\n\nFWIW, on the same laptop, I get\n\n* Windows aarch64 running via UTM+QEMU (trunk compiled from source)\n\n  ```\n  $ .\/bin\/Rscript.exe -e 'sprintf(\"%a\", 0.9999999999999999)'\n  [1] \"0x1p+0\"\n  ```\n\n* But Debian aarch64 via UTM+Apple Virtualization (trunk compiled from source)\n\n  ```\n  $ Rscript -e 'sprintf(\"%a\", 0.9999999999999999)'\n  [1] \"0x1.fffffffffffffp-1\"\n  ```\n\nThe last is true both when compiled using GNU compilers and with LLVM compilers\n(I had initially thought it might have something to do with that as both macOS\nand Windows uses clang).",
